<div class="big-head">
    <h1>{% trans "How to format data for Data Wrapper" %}.</h1>
</div>


<div style="text-align:center; margin: 20px 0 40px">
<p>
    For a basic horizontal or vertical bar chart, each bar should be on a separate row, with one column for the bar's label (in this case, on the x axis) and another for the bar's value. In this example, column headers are not displayed on the graph. Graph titles are entered manually, separate from the source data.

</p>
</div>
<div style="text-align:center; margin: 20px 0 40px">
    <img src = "/static/img/wapo/bar_chart_data.png">
    <span style = "font-size:38px">&#10142;</span>
    <img src = "/static/img/wapo/bar_chart_example.png" style = "width:300px">
</div>

<div style="text-align:center; margin: 20px 0 40px">
<p>
    For a stacked bar chart <strong>or</strong> a grouped bar chart, you should enter data as shown below. Note that, compared to the above example, the rows and columns have been switched. Now, each <em>column</em> corresponds to a separate bar, and each row corresponds to a facet of the data (i.e. either a group or a stack). You can also swap the rows and columns of any data set after you've uploaded it, by clicking the <strong>transpose the data</strong> link during the <strong>Visualize</strong> step.
</p>
</div>
<div style="text-align:center; margin: 20px 0 40px">
    <img src = "/static/img/wapo/stacked_bar_data.png">
    <span style = "font-size:38px">&#10142;</span>
    <img src = "/static/img/wapo/stacked_bar_example.png" style = "width:300px">
</div>

<div style="text-align:center; margin: 20px 0 40px">
<p>
    For a basic line chart, each column corresponds to a seaparte line, and each row corresponds to a value on the x axis. The key is automatically generated based on the column headers.

</p>
</div>
<div style="text-align:center; margin: 20px 0 40px">
    <img src = "/static/img/wapo/line_chart_data.png">
    <span style = "font-size:38px">&#10142;</span>
    <img src = "/static/img/wapo/line_chart_example.png" style = "width:300px">
</div>


